# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1808 Connecticut gubernatorial election** took place on April 14, 1808.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Federalist Governor Jonathan Trumbull Jr. won re-election to an eleventh full term, defeating Democratic-Republican candidate William Hart in a re-match of the previous year's election.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1808 Connecticut lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on April 11, 1808, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of Connecticut.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Federalist lieutenant governor John Treadwell defeated Democratic-Republican candidate Asa Spalding in a re-match of the previous year's election.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 11, 1808, incumbent Federalist lieutenant governor John Treadwell won re-election by a margin of 5,917 votes against his opponent Democratic-Republican candidate Asa Spalding, thereby retaining Federalist control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Treadwell was sworn in for his eleventh term on May 12, 1808.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The **1808–09 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 26, 1808, and May 5, 1809.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 11th United States Congress convened on May 22, 1809.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] They coincided with James Madison being elected as president.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Elections were held for all 142 seats, representing 17 states.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Despite Madison's victory, voters in districts whose economies were driven by shipping or manufacturing rather than agriculture shifted to the Federalist Party.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The reasons for this shift were the unpopularity of the Embargo Act of 1807 and fears that Democratic-Republican Party policies could trigger a naval war with the First French Empire or Britain.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The politically dominant Democratic-Republicans won their smallest majority since the pivotal, realigning election of 1800.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] There were special elections in 1808 and 1809 during the 10th United States Congress and 11th United States Congress.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Elections are sorted here by date then district.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Between the 1806 and 1808 elections, New York went through a redistricting that reduced the number of districts to 15 by creating two plural districts with two seats each.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] This brought the state's 17-seat delegation from a 15-2 ratio favoring Democratic-Republicans to a nearly-even 9–8 split in their favor.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Three territories sent non-voting delegates to the 11th Congress.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Indiana Territory elected by popular vote for the first time.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Mississippi Territory also elected its delegate by popular vote.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-indiana-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Orleans Territory retained legislative election of its delegate.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] The **1808 Kentucky gubernatorial election** was held on August 1, 1808, in order to elect the Governor of Kentucky.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate Charles Scott defeated fellow Democratic-Republican candidates John Allen and Green Clay.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 1, 1808, Democratic-Republican candidate Charles Scott won the election by a margin of 13,620 votes against his foremost opponent fellow Democratic-Republican candidate John Allen, thereby retaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of governor.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Scott was sworn in as the 4th governor of Kentucky on August 23, 1808.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-new-hampshire-gubernatorial-election] The **1808 New Hampshire gubernatorial election** was held on March 8, 1808.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-new-hampshire-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic-Republican Governor John Langdon won re-election to a fourth term.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-new-hampshire-gubernatorial-election] The following candidates may not have been formally nominated and attracted only scattering votes.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-new-york-s-12th-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** was held in **New York's 12th congressional district** on April 26–28, 1808 to fill a vacancy left by the resignation, on February 5, 1808, of David Thomas (DR), who had been appointed New York State Treasurer.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-new-york-s-12th-congressional-district-special-election] This election was held at the same time as the 1808 Congressional elections.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-new-york-s-12th-congressional-district-special-election] As New York had redistricted in the meantime, Thomas' former district no longer existed as a separate district, but was now a part of the 6th district.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** was held in **North Carolina's 7th congressional district** on February 1, 1808.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election] In the 1806 elections, John Culpepper (F) had defeated incumbent Duncan McFarlan (DR), but McFarlan contested the election, and, on January 2, 1808, the House Committee on Elections declared the seat vacant.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election] Culpepper was thus returned to the House, resuming his seat on February 23, 1808.
[src:1808-north-carolina-s-7th-congressional-district-special-election/1808-pennsylvania-s-1st-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** was held in **Pennsylvania's 1st congressional district** on October 11, 1808, to fill a vacancy left by the resignation of Joseph Clay (DR) on March 28, 1808.
